reviews.text: A friend and I were exploring the city and upon leaving the church we spoke to a lady who then walked us around and informed us of other places to see. The generous woman also offered to buy us drinks/food at Manor before we parted ways. We kindly refused but she was lovely. What a wonderful woman.

Beautiful and unique inside. Wonderful example of a protestant church after all the Catholic ones I have visited in Spain and Italy. Tower worth the climb as the views are amazing out across the lake and the old town. Make sure to keep going up too!
Beautiful cathedral and a must-see of Geneva. The view from the top should not be missed. The underground visit is interesting too.

Beautiful cathedral and the home cathedral of the famous John Calvin. Stained glass is excellent as expected. The cathedral is the size you’d expect from one build in the 15th century. If you are looking for a quick tour to be able to take pics and go, you could be in and out in less than 20 minutes.
Absolutely stunning views on a clear day. I highly recommend paying to go up in the towers!

An altogether superb experience wherein the seat of world power can be experienced in a beautiful surrounding. Some peaceful demonstration was going on and that added to the whole feel of the place. Felt great to see so many countries and different cultures coming together at one place. Definitely recommend and coming back again :)

A really big place. But reaching it once we cross the main gates is a little confusing and especially gruelling to persons with physical disabilities. Those moving around in a wheelchair can do so very easily as accessibility is perfect. But for those not using one, very difficult. One of my friends was suggesting if they were to have some carts around for disabled people to move in and around, it would make this place the most accessible on the planet.
Stunningly beautiful architecture & building interiors, along with senior diplomats & ambassadors from 193 countries around the world... hard-core multilingual & multicultural, love it, wow!

A must visit if you are visiting Geneva. If you are looking to not go inside but just spend time outside, give it 30 mins to 1 hour depending on how many photos you would like to click at the UN and the broker chair which are at the same location.
Great guided tours for most languages and the views are stunning alongside the eclectic mix of art. The huge giant steps leading to where the general assembly meets are extravagant.

Stumbled upon the monument as I was walking along the lake side. The ornate building got my attention so I had to cross the street to get a closer look. It looked like there was a coffin in the mid layer of the structure. There were also quite a few water features around (but they were all off at the time). It was a really interesting stop especially if you enjoy elaborate carvings.

This is another great photo opportunity in Geneva. It is a fantastic example of extravagant, Neo-Gothic architecture. You can view it from the waterfront, but may prefer to get photos from the park, with the waterfront (and the fountain) as your backdrop. In park grounds, this is a good place to enjoy a stroll or break up a long walk with children.
Very appealing architecture... It might have been awesome if they would have arranged some lights in the night.
Interesting monument in the middle of a beautiful city. A short stop by for a photo op is all that is needed.
nice spot. very romantic. a bit windy so come wih coat.

Fantastic Sunday Brunch. Kids & Pet friendly environment. Great food. The decor is unlike anything else in Geneva. The ambience and the location of the place is perfect. Different events during some evenings, you can check with their program on Social Media.

I was in Geneva for a meeting before Christmas and the organizers held drinks and dinner at this venue. This place was spacious and very relaxed, with generous views overlooking the Rhone river!
Super friendly service and delicious local dishes. I had such a wonderful evening. Met a lot of really cool people after dinner on the dance floor around this "Gorgeous" center pc Bar - Truly stunning design.
I highly recommend this place to any travelers, locals & event goers!

This place is grand. I’ve stopped in for drinks many times. Food is very good and reasonably priced. Relaxed atmosphere.  Choice for after hours, late night weekends, Sunday brunch and Special Events.

One brasserie going long way back. Even if you think it is too touristic the location is unique for a stop between site seeing. I visited in winter time, but I'm sure that in the hot summer days many visitors move around with a cool beer.

Beautiful located within the River Rhone with great Windows. Decent and very well priced food offering especially if you like Burgers. Friendly and considerate staff. The low seats are a little bit inconvenient for taller people. Also good for families.
Open only on weekends from 11 am

This park is worth a visit if you are passing through in this direction. They have informative placards up to provide an education about the various plants. The different species of palms are well displayed. If you're curious to explore, you could likely spend up to 45 minutes wandering around.
A pleasant place to spend an afternoon. Lots of information (in French) about the various trees and plants of French Guiana.
Frankly, these gardens were not too well kept. Many of the sidewalks were cracked, and there wasn't too much foliage or plant life.
It's free. You get what you pay for..

This is one of the best museums in Geneva. The three main exhibitions are hugely educational while also being entertaining and interactive. You can have a headset in your language that guides you around the museum, which I found very useful, although it did sometimes play the wrong recording when moving in the more crowded exhibits (chambers of witnesses). On the whole, the headset worked very well, and the restaurant was good as well. The temporary exhibition was great as well, although I must say, regarding the whole museum, it can be useful to have some background knowledge before you go in, and it is best if you understand the topics inside, so I think that it is best if you are over 13.

Probably one of the best museums in Geneva. Very educational and unexpectedly interactive. Not a demanding one as well, you’ll need no more than two hours for a detailed visit. Headsets are automatically playing when you enter the room which is a nice quirk, with additional explanation on the way. It’s educational, but not politically charged which I liked, however some issues could have been given a bit more space

Excellent narrated walk around tour provided by a headset available in a number of different languages. The only reason it is not 5/5 is because the headset occasionally cut out or repeated the narration a number of times. That aside, an excellent and thought provoking experience that provided fantastic insight in to the incredibly important work done by the Red Cross over a very long period of time.

Go and visit to inform yourself on the Red Cross and what they do around the world and throughout modern history. Get the headphones so you can hear in your own language all the stories and information. Well worth the entrance fee and the journey from the city centre. Also located near the Ariana and United Nations

Probably the best attraction in Geneva. Very informative and moving. It’s interactive takes you not just through the history of the International Red Cross, but also through the experiences of people who lived through the disasters and wars that are served from the Red Cross. The World War I missing persons registry was particularly moving. Probably not great for young children, but older children who can deal with more sensitive issues will probably enjoy the interactive nature of it.

The museum spans over a few floors full of impressive artworks. Every room takes you into a different world. The staff is super friendly and helpful and we were very lucky to come here on the first Sunday of the month which meant free entry for us. Almost beats TATE in London. Allow at least 1.5-2 hours to see everything
Absolutly brilliant ! You have to go there more than once
Fantastic museum, a real gem hidden in Geneva. Kind staff with tons of knowledge to share

Mamco...what to say. At the entrance we had to wait for 1,5 hour to get in. Then, the security obliges you to put your bag in a sort of cloak room. 
At the “cloak room” there are small safety boxes and you have to have a 2 CHF piece and cram in your outwear in this small box including your handbag. 
The elevators are not working, so prepare to be in a good sport shape and climb the stairs. 
As for the art itself. I don’t pretend to be a  connoisseur of painting or contemporary art in general, however I can’t consider the mountain of trash as an art. 
For me, Mamco building in Geneva is neither a gallery, nor a museum.
It is an ok museum. Not at all comparable to modern art museums in major cities worldwide.
Nice presented art museum. 10 min walking distance from Fribourg station and just two blocks away from Cathedral St Nicholas.

A great museum, well worth the visit. Everything is very nicely presented and of particular interest is the work of the female artist Marcello from the late 19th century. Also within the museum is part of the 13th century town wall.
Quite interesting for one-time visit
Such art. Very history

Le plein d'informations sur l'histoire sans oublier l'histoire religieuse du canton de Fribourg. Le musée étonne aussi par sa grandeur et la qualité de son bâtiment. Je recommande vivement une visite qui en vaut le détour. N'oubliez pas de prendre l'aide audio qui augmente beaucoup les détails des objets exposés.

Loved this! One of the best experiences I had in Geneva. These are true works of art, showcasing art styles and historical landmarks in clock making. I had no idea there would be that much to be awed by (clocks are not the most mystifying thing that comes to mind usually), but there really was. Just beautiful!

Extraordinary museum with enormous collection of watches! Prepare yourself for several hours of visiting this place! The best option is to join a free (included in the ticket price, check the hours on their website) tour to get to know the history of the company and some interesting facts about selected watches. Amazing experience and a must see when in Geneva area!

Fabulous collection of watches, goes through the history of timekeeping.

I'd advise to start on the 3rd floor, as they say, and then work your way down 

Also ensure you get the audio guide/ iPad. Very well thought out!
No photography allowed inside. It is very interesting even if you are  not into watches. The collection of timepieces is impressive some date to 1530.
Incredible and beautiful. An absolute must see. I was staggered that such beautiful miniature paintings could be created 300 years ago on watch cases.

This was a great little museum. The second floor apartment is actually the least interesting bit, and is detracted from by an unusual curitorial focus on items' make rather their use/function/context.  What is much more interesting is artistry of doors and other bits and bobs of stunning craftsmanship displayed on the first floor. 
The ground floor and third floor together also help to give the visitor a really excellent overview of the city's history and geography. I'd recommend making this part of day 1 of your trip so you can quite literally get the lay of the land. 
The museum is free, and you should be able to get through it in an hour. 
The beginning presentation and guided interpretation are available in English, but signs throughout the museum are French.

The kitchen part was fun to see because it showed a lot of different old kitchen tools, and on that level they showed different antique wallpapers as well. The rest of the levels didn't have a clear goal / didn't explain well what everything was about.

I visited the Maison Tavel as part of the escalade so I didn't see the entire museum. The parts I did see, however, were very nicely laid out with an explanation on one of the core songs of the celebration translated and explained. A fun experience, for sure.
oldest house in town, go to top floor, you'll love the reduced scale model of geneva
If you’re in Geneva, Switzerland then this place is a must to visit. This quaint little museum in the old part of the city is the best way to get a historic overview of Geneva from its beginnings.

I heard about this concept in London and came across them in Geneva by coincidence.   The atmosphere is super cool, staff perfect, and food delicious.

I am a regular now

Fun and friendly place with a very short menu but what they do they do, they do  very well and with a smile! The Kosovan waiter ( sorry I can’t remember your name) was professional, efficient and kind. I would headhunt him if I had a restaurant !

What a pleasant surprise. I mean, eating seafood in a landlocked country is not alway a great idea but this place was excellent. I had the lobster and it was cooked perfectly. My friends who had steaks were also very happy with their meal. Cocktails were also amazing and I recommend the passion for mule one. Service was a little slow since they are minimally staffed but the waiter and barman were friendly and polite. Prices are very reasonable.

Do not pass this gem up! We were surprised that this Quaint restaurant could handle our party of 13 as we walked off the street. The staff was friendly accommodating and even cheerful. The food was amazing, the steak tender and perfectly cooked the lobster some of the most succulent I have ever had. If that wasn't enough the desserts finish the meal and tantalize the pallet in the best way.
You get either beef or lobster. Sort of strange. But good quality service and food

The best café/restaurant/bar! This place satisfies a whole range of different food categories: steak, hamburger, pasta and salads, omelettes, and multiple drinks! Also, there are a lot of delicios foods, cakes and beverages for people with food allergies and intolerances and vegans ❤ Enjoy your stay with good music and vibes in the background 👌
Always confort and cozy place,  like the vegan cake tgey have and there is a good choice of tea
Friendly place and tasty food. Just wandered in, had their dish of the day, some coffee,wine etc. Also, they play better music in here then you will hear in most places in Switzerland. Recommended.
Cozy place for dinner or a drink.
It is a very nice cosy place but i would suggest they add a bit more vents so the smell of the fries goes down, other than that loved it :)
Amazing sandwiches and burgers. Corn bread is great. Could be a little more of choices though..
Good burgers, the place is a bit tiny

Best burger I have ever ate.  Delicious.  Have to try for yourself.  Expensive but worth it.  There is not much room outside of the restaraunt to sit on the street so don't bring much with you.  Other than that, relax and enjoy it.
So good, so good! The burger (burger of the month) was awesome, medium rare, just the way I like it. Cozy atmosphere and their own beer it goes perfect with the food. Totally worth it!
Tasteful burgers at a reasonable price, definitely visiting again
Price are to expensive for a "fast food"
No nonsense asian fast food. Friendly/efficient/clean.
Crevettes  menu is missing way too many crevettes...I would prefer to have more crevettes than starch...
People say that Slender Man used to eat her. Pat Thai ok! *here
I ate twice, I could not finish the dish, Its not fresh and not delicious, even Coca Cola is not the taste of coca

I liked their food. It was a big serving size and tasty. They have halal meat so that is great! 

Although it was 'Geneva pricing' i.e. €20 for a meal. Coming from London, I'd not pay more than £10 for a similar meal. But it's Switzerland so you pay double.
Again, an amazing experience. Out of this world tasting food, authentic Turkish cuisine and the wait staff is helpful beyond description. A place worth going to, over and over and over.
Nice place to eat out. Their chicKen and rice is fantastic
Good service. This place is halal with certificates on the wall but do serve alcohol. Food was ok, nothing to shout about but prices were expensive, 10 Euros for a kebab sandwich!
Very tasty and good price.

Avoid!! 

I don't expect best quality sushi from a take-away but this is really the worst take away sushi I have ever had. 
It starts with the order. All Nigiri sushi pictures show sets of 2 pieces but the ordering amount appears on delivery to be per piece. So expect to pay double compared to other take away sushi (45 CHF for 15 pieces!!!).
On top the sushi portions are really small and despite I am experienced with chop sticks, the rice drops of as soon as you touch them.
Also ordered Wakame.....tasteless
Also ordered Kimuchi......tasteles, raw cole nothing to do with kimuchi

Plenty of wasabi (14 pockets) and soya (10 "fish" shaped portions) though....

I would say it is a rip-off

Worst meal I've ever had... The chicken was disgusting and tasted like plastic. The rice was very badly done and was absolutely tasteless. I DO NOT RECOMMEND THIS PLACE TO ANYONE. Don't come here! Awful food and awful service.
Sushi exquid

Wide variety of different assorted alternatives.
Good quality, standard but good.
Clean, quick and easy.
I thought it was good quality price and 9 hours later I am paying the price! Avoid it!
Family run, Vietnamese/Chinese/Malaysian cuisine. Authentic. Generous portions.
Delicious Asian specialties cooked with fresh products and served by a nice family. Not easy to decide which dish to eat as every thing looks yummy.
Good food, low price and fast service
Best bang for your buck Asian restaurant in Geneva
Teasty,cheap and fast

Definitely a restaurant to stop at if visiting Geneva. The staff was very friendly and the food was exceptional. I ordered the warm lentil salad and my friend order the pan fried cheese with green salad. Prices were typical for the area. Thank you for such a good meal :)

It is a bit far from the city center, about a 10 minute walk from the United Nations palace. 
The area was in felt like an olden day village with a church and small shops around. The restaurant itself also looked quite old.
I booked by email beforehand since I had half a day in the city and wanted to try this place since other reviews and blogs had said it was the best place for fondue. They had quite a bit of seating area downstairs and they also had a second floor with an outdoor balcony. 
Once seated I got a menu and started to peruse through it. I got some still water since I didn't know you had to specify for tap water. There were quite a few items on the menu which looked interesting but I did come for the fondue. The bread came out first followed by the boiling pot of cheese. The bread was a bit stale on its own (which I'm guessing is normal) but when dipped into the cheese it was magnificent. Surprisingly it was cool enough to eat after taking the cheese from the pot. I did run out of cheese though and so the last few bits of bread weren't as good as the previous ones. I also had the profiteroles for dessert and they were nice but the pastry wasn't crispy.
Although a bit far it was a nice area to walk around in. The fondue was really nice and I really liked the fact that it didn't split so you didn't have to mix it, just dip in the bread and eat.
Good place. The lentil salad was amazing! A half portion was more than enough. Also, if ordering other items, 1 fondue for 2 people is more than enough.

Wonderful fondue and wine. We had a fondue to share which was amazing with bread. We had the house wine and kir (which even my non drinking sister loved) the desserts looked amazing but we were just too full to have anymore. Easy to get to on tram 3 from the central train station.
Very informal family friendly local Swiss restaurant! Famous thanks to their fondue! Nice and typical place! Recommended!
We were a bit cramped but the restaurant is very welcoming and tasty. Thank you for your cheerfulness!

A small French bistro with great food. We had bone marrow, lamb and steak and they were all magnificent. The ladies ( I think they were the owners) were very friendly and intimate. Definitely go there again.
Great food, great service a really nice place in Geneva
One of the best braised beef doshes ive ever had.

Good experience and specially if you booked a table through the fork. Feels like Lyon in Geneva. Try out Le Socrate too, it seems that it is managed by the same guys!
We recommand for a table surrounded by friends!
Follow us on instagram @gojiandbear
It was really bad quality food and the staff are really careless and rude. I took a piece that was contaminated and i went to hospitall for two days. Honestly waste of money.
Food very good. Service very slow. Only enjoyable if you can wait.
Possibly the best tuna sashimi I've ever had. This place is the real deal. I understand that the Japanese ambassador only eats 🍣 from here when he's in Geneva.
Great quality, nice deco. Good service.  Keep it going
One of the best sushi restaurant in Geneva !
The entrecote melted in our mouth. Overall very good food. Nice discovery.

Best restaurant in town as far as I'm concerned.  Maurice and Gina, the husband / wife owners, have created a culinary haven, where you can enjoy the finest steaks in a French bistro atmosphere.  When you walk in, you can immediately tell that at least half of the clientele are locals who dine there regularly.  The familiar atmosphere is enhanced by the fact that the chef and owners take time to greet each client personally.  A really gem !!
Delicious food and quick service
Decent. No complaints. The chef knows his cuissons. Sauce was a bit oily and chips were from the freezer, which I didn't expect given the prices, but overall an enjoyable meal and good service.
Classic! Entrecôte what else! Cote de boeuf maybe! Simple but perfect! Limited wine list.

Nice spacious location with food and coffee to offer. However, I found the sandwiches to be very pricey for what they were, even though they were quite tasty. The welcome was friendly and pleasant and the staff was more than willing to explain anything or offer to alter one of their sandwich recipes to your liking. The location is not particularly accessible for mobility impaired individuals and the toilets are quite small. Would probably visit again in the future, but will most likely stick to a beverage as opposed to food.
Ahh Edwards...always a delicious address for a quick lunch with panini or a salad. My tip is panini with pain de campagne. Detox juices are very good.
Good option for a cheap and fresh food in the center of the city!
Great place to grab a quick sandwich. However, there is a bigger Edwards across the lake. But they are all very tasty. Very friendly staff.
The best vegetarian burger (Tendergreen) with egg and the cheese.  Good service and quality food and a reasonable price. A+
Friendly welcome and good food
Food is alright. Friendly staff. Price is Okey too.
OK at best
Normal

Très bon service, patrons accueillants et on y mange très bien !
Philippe

Visited this place as a group of 3 children and 2 adults. I would say good service overall, and amazing burger. We also ordered a steak and mussels and 2 more items which I cannot remember. The management could have been more polite. Even though we needed a table for an hour only, the man who appeared to be the head waiter was difficult and unfriendly over it. Eventually we were sat at a good table by the lovely waitress, quickly ate and left with our children. So he needn't stress about vacating our table for guests who would probably not arrive for another hour or so.

The place seemed promising due to reviews and the great deco inside. Our dining experience was a little disappointing; staff didn't seem very friendly nor welcoming (we did not have a reservation). The waiter at our table was plain rude, abrupt. For instance, my plate was burning hot but I was not told to be careful. I speak French, so the language barrier is no issue. He did not explain how to work the gas dish-warmer that came with the vegetarian dish and he did not care when I mentioned there were bits of cork in my red wine. Luckily, another kind waiter saw us trying to figure things out and he helped. I had the grilled veal (I had better, I had worse). Burger was really good, I tried a bit. All in all, a decent meal but we wouldn't go back.

Lovely.  A bit too busy and all the tables are squashed next to each other. (we really didn't appreciate that)  That is a shame as even the waiter had a tough time serving and clearing. We had to help him. The food however was extraordinary. The service staff exceptional.  Maybe try the terrace it looks more spacious.

The food is good and the service too but in summer you can easily sit on the bird excrement and become dirty while restaurant do not care. Also plant of flies in summer as we ordered a big plate to share and literally they were sitting at every peace of it and flying all around us, while restaurant again do not care and did not propose us any discount or apologized...

Typical French cuisine with wide choice of dishes and wines from different parts of France, with special focus on oysters and it delivers! It’s a bit squeezed in terms of space, but it doesn’t bother. The biggest minus is the service - not very friendly, and much too slow, especially for a place that sells upscale brassiere experience. The prices are on the expensive side

This place is always great! The staff is very nice and helpful, the food is really good and there is always attention to detail. They are always child friendly and will go out of their way to make sure that you’re comfortable and have what you need for a good night. I really do recommend this place for a nice and casual dinner out.
The pizzas are surprisingly good and made with fresh ingredients.
Nice surroundings of Carouge. Terrace. Nice Italian food in a hipster local.
Went for a "plat du jour". One of the worst lasagna I ever ate. They wouldn't dare serving this in Italy...
Excellent food and service
